    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Introduction to Gifts and the Verb 'To Give'"
        },
        "text": "When we talk about gifts in Arabic, the most common word is 'هدية'. The verb 'to give' can be expressed in several ways, but a common one related to gifts is 'أهدى' (ahdā) or more generally 'أعطى' (a'ṭā).",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "هدية",
            "english": "Gift",
            "transliteration": "Hadiyya",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The 'a' at the end is a feminine marker (tā’ marbūṭa)."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "أعطى",
            "english": "He gave (verb)",
            "transliteration": "A'ṭā",
            "diacriticalNotes": "Basic past tense verb form."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "أهدى",
            "english": "He gifted (verb)",
            "transliteration": "Ahdā",
            "diacriticalNotes": "Specifically means 'to give a gift'."
          }
        ],
        "audioText": "هدية. أعطى. أهدى."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'What do you like?'"
        },
        "text": "To ask someone what they like in Arabic, you use 'ماذا تُحِبُّ؟' (What do you like?). The verb 'تُحِبُّ' changes slightly depending on if you are addressing a male or a female. Pay attention to the verb endings.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "ماذا تُحِبُّ؟",
            "english": "What do you (male) like?",
            "transliteration": "Mādhā tuḥibbu?",
            "diacriticalNotes": "Damma on the last 'ب' distinguishes male singular present tense from the female form."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "ماذا تُحِبِّينَ؟",
            "english": "What do you (female) like?",
            "transliteration": "Mādhā tuḥibbīna?",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The 'ينَ' ending indicates feminine singular present tense."
          }
        ],
        "audioText": "ماذا تُحِبُّ؟ ماذا تُحِبِّينَ؟"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Expressing 'I like...'"
        },
        "text": "To express what you like, you use 'أُحِبُّ' (uḥibbu). This form is used by both males and females. You can then follow it with the noun or phrase you like.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "أُحِبُّ القهوة.",
            "english": "I like coffee.",
            "transliteration": "Uḥibbu al-qahwa.",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The 'أُ' and 'بُّ' make the pronunciation of 'I like' clear."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "أُحِبُّ الهدايا.",
            "english": "I like gifts.",
            "transliteration": "Uḥibbu al-hadāyā.",
            "diacriticalNotes": "Plural of هدية."
          }
        ],
        "audioText": "أُحِبُّ القهوة. أُحِبُّ الهدايا."
      }
    },
