    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Talking About Giving a Gift: 'I will give you...'"
        },
        "text": "When you want to say 'I will give you (a gift)', you can use 'سَأُهديكَ' (sa'uhdīka) for a male or 'سَأُهديكِ' (sa'uhdīki) for a female. The 'سَـ' (sa-) prefix indicates the future tense. Another option is 'سَأُقَدِّمُ لكَ/لكِ' (sa'uqaddimu laka/laki) meaning 'I will present to you'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "سَأُهديكَ كتاباً.",
            "english": "I will give you (male) a book (as a gift).",
            "transliteration": "Sa'uhdīka kitāban.",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The 'كَ' indicates the male direct object pronoun. 'اً' is tanwīn for indefinite accusative."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "سَأُقَدِّمُ لكِ زهوراً.",
            "english": "I will present you (female) with flowers.",
            "transliteration": "Sa'uqaddimu laki zuhūran.",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The 'لكِ' indicates 'to you' (female). 'اً' is tanwīn for indefinite accusative."
          }
        ],
        "audioText": "سَأُهديكَ كتاباً. سَأُقَدِّمُ لكِ زهوراً."
      }
