    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Polite Refusal or Expressing a Different Preference"
        },
        "text": "If you need to politely express a different preference, you can use 'أُفَضِّلُ أن...' (ufaḍḍilu an...) meaning 'I prefer to...' or directly 'أُفَضِّلُ ...' (ufaḍḍilu...) meaning 'I prefer...'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "شكراً، لكنني أُفَضِّلُ الكتبَ.",
            "english": "Thank you, but I prefer books.",
            "transliteration": "Shukran, lākinanī ufaḍḍilu al-kutuba.",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The 'أُفَضِّلُ' form is for 'I prefer'."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "أُفَضِّلُ أن أختارَ هديتي بنفسي.",
            "english": "I prefer to choose my gift myself.",
            "transliteration": "Ufaḍḍilu an akhtāra hadiyyatī binafsī.",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The 'أختارَ' has a fatha due to 'أن'."
          }
        ],
        "audioText": "شكراً، لكنني أُفَضِّلُ الكتبَ. أُفَضِّلُ أن أختارَ هديتي بنفسي."
